                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.74/210: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-01-10T20:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 10, 1922—8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4. With reference to your telegram of January 6, no. 5, you are informed that the
                    American Government will not assent to the setting up in China by foreign
                    private companies or by foreign powers of any arrangement which will impose
                    either a cable, radio or telegraph monopoly upon China. As far as Chinese
                    communications are concerned any understanding arrived at will only be reached
                    after the fullest consultation with the Chinese Government representatives, This
                    Government maintains its previous attitude toward the Federal Telegraph
                    Company’s contract and it is expected by the Department that the Federal
                    Telegraph Company’s understanding with the Chinese Government will be possible
                    of execution by the company.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
